<div id="p376" class="blockpost rowodd">
	<h2><span><span class="conr">#7&nbsp;</span><a href="viewtopic.php?pid=376#p376">2008-08-20 17:01:46</a></span></h2>
	<div class="box">
		<div class="inbox">
			<div class="postleft">
				<dl>
					<dt><strong><a href="profile.php?id=89618">The 8472</a></strong></dt>
					<dd class="usertitle"><strong>Azureus Developer</strong></dd>
					<dd class="postavatar"></dd>
				</dl>
			</div>
			<div class="postright">
				<h3> Re: bep 27: private torrents</h3>
				<div class="postmsg">
					<p>no, that is not the concern. The private flag turns off all external peer sources, thus confining peer lists to individual trackers. This only works if all clients get a copy of the .torrent that has the private flag set otherwise they would announce it via DHT and other clients which also have a copy w/o the private flag could get it via DHT.<br /><br />So, a single client with a modified copy of the .torrent could compromise the entire private swarm with pex+dht. If it changes the infohash then this won't be the case anymore as it it'll be a new swarm.<br /><br />While the private flag does rely on conformance by all clients, putting the flag into the .torrent does not require conformance of all versions of the .torrent. And it makes user manipulation harder.</p>
					<p class="postedit"><em>Last edited by The 8472 (2008-08-20 17:02:51)</em></p>
				</div>
				<div class="postsignature"><hr />Az dev</div>
			</div>
			<div class="clearer"></div>
			<div class="postfootleft"><p>Offline</p></div>
			<div class="postfootright"><div>&nbsp;</div></div>
		</div>
	</div>
</div>

<div id="p408" class="blockpost roweven">
	<h2><span><span class="conr">#8&nbsp;</span><a href="viewtopic.php?pid=408#p408">2008-08-29 22:35:10</a></span></h2>
	<div class="box">
		<div class="inbox">
			<div class="postleft">
				<dl>
					<dt><strong><a href="profile.php?id=89601">dave</a></strong></dt>
					<dd class="usertitle"><strong>Editor</strong></dd>
					<dd class="postavatar"></dd>
				</dl>
			</div>
			<div class="postright">
				<h3> Re: bep 27: private torrents</h3>
				<div class="postmsg">
					<p>An attacker Alice can thwart the &quot;private marking&quot; if Alice obtains the .torrent file and adds tracker URLs to non-private trackers.&nbsp; The tracker URLs are outside the info dict and thus can be modified without modifying the id of the torrent.&nbsp; Alice then posts the .torrent file to a public tracker web site.<br /><br />Unsuspecting Bob logs into the private tracker website.&nbsp; This login enables his IP to use the private tracker.&nbsp; Meandering Bob downloads Alice's modified .torrent file from the public website.&nbsp; Bob's client sees the private=1 key-value pair inside the info dict and adheres to its strictures.&nbsp; Bob's client anonunces to both the public and private tracker (his client thinks both are private trackers).&nbsp; However the public tracker employs no access control.&nbsp; Thus Bob now acts as a conduit between the public and private torrent thus allowing the bits to escape.<br /><br />If the private=1 key were outside the info dict then it could be remove entirely without modifying the infohash which would magnify the problem.&nbsp; Now not only would Bob act as a conduit for the bits of the file, but he would also hand out references to the private peers via PEX thus effectively allowing the private and public subswarms to completely merge into a single swarm.<br /><br />Either attack allows an attacker to subvert an unsuspecting person with access to the private tracker.&nbsp; The second attack however is worse by degree.&nbsp; We just have ask ourselves whether this is a signifcant threat.&nbsp; If it is not then we can allow the private=1 key to reside outside the info dict.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="clearer"></div>
			<div class="postfootleft"><p>Offline</p></div>
			<div class="postfootright"><div>&nbsp;</div></div>
		</div>
	</div>
</div>

