<div id="p435" class="blockpost rowodd">
	<h2><span><span class="conr">#13&nbsp;</span><a href="viewtopic.php?pid=435#p435">2008-09-02 17:24:11</a></span></h2>
	<div class="box">
		<div class="inbox">
			<div class="postleft">
				<dl>
					<dt><strong><a href="profile.php?id=30435">bram</a></strong></dt>
					<dd class="usertitle"><strong>Administrator</strong></dd>
					<dd class="postavatar"></dd>
				</dl>
			</div>
			<div class="postright">
				<h3> Re: bep 27: private torrents</h3>
				<div class="postmsg">
					<blockquote><div class="incqbox"><h4>The 8472 wrote:</h4><p>If you put it outside the info dict the user can manipulate it and thus override the torrent-publisher's intention. If the torrent-publisher wants to change it later he can just remove the private flag and publish a new torrent.</p></div></blockquote><p>The 'user' can do anything they want - it's their client.<br /><br />To speak of an attack there most be a threat model here. As I see it, the threat here isn't that a client machine leaks information (of course the client machine can leak information, to suggest otherwise is absurd) but that another site copies the .torrent file over, modifies the private flag, slurps some peers from the old tracker, and then proceeds to serve up the new .torrent. This can be done regardless of where the private flag is, but it will work somewhat better if the private flag is outside the info dict, because then peer exchange will happen between peers from the new site, so they won't be restricted to the set of peers which the new site's tracker slurped (although slurping a whole bunch of peers isn't exactly infeasible).<br /><br />If anyone has a different threat model, I'd like to hear it, because that's the only one I can see.<br /><br />The amount of defense here is pretty weak. There would be far more justification for putting the tracker url optionally inside the info dict, which would make it impossible for a new site to copy over the .torrent file and change the tracker, at least without client help or setting up a seed of their own. I'm perfectly happy to discuss an optional tracker url inside the info dict, to insist on the private flag being inside the info dict without even suggesting that the tracker url be is just ridiculous.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="clearer"></div>
			<div class="postfootleft"><p>Offline</p></div>
			<div class="postfootright"><div>&nbsp;</div></div>
		</div>
	</div>
