<div id="p437" class="blockpost roweven">
	<h2><span><span class="conr">#14&nbsp;</span><a href="viewtopic.php?pid=437#p437">2008-09-02 18:34:09</a></span></h2>
	<div class="box">
		<div class="inbox">
			<div class="postleft">
				<dl>
					<dt><strong><a href="profile.php?id=89618">The 8472</a></strong></dt>
					<dd class="usertitle"><strong>Azureus Developer</strong></dd>
					<dd class="postavatar"></dd>
				</dl>
			</div>
			<div class="postright">
				<h3> Re: bep 27: private torrents</h3>
				<div class="postmsg">
					<p>I suggest you talk to a private tracker admin. They don't want their users to un-private a torrent, hence it's in the info-dict. It's as simple as that.<br /><br /></p><blockquote><div class="incqbox"><p>The amount of defense here is pretty weak.</p></div></blockquote><p>It's what everyone is happy with. It's established, nobody who's actually using it has raised issues with it. Since we are not stakeholders in this i suggest we do not change it until someone demonstrates practical need for it.<br /><br /></p><blockquote><div class="incqbox"><p>to insist on the private flag being inside the info dict without even suggesting that the tracker url be is just ridiculous.</p></div></blockquote><p>No. The semantics are simple. The private flag simply confines the swarm to the currently used tracker as peer source. Multiple private trackers could host the same torrent, with the same infohash but the swarms won't intermix as PEX, DHT, lan peer discovery are all disabled. Thus the flag independent of the tracker URL and indicates &quot;this torrent should only use 1 tracker at a time and nothing else&quot;. That's it.</p>
					<p class="postedit"><em>Last edited by The 8472 (2008-09-02 18:43:27)</em></p>
				</div>
				<div class="postsignature"><hr />Az dev</div>
			</div>
